**Bipartite matching.** Note that our neural network would always predict 25 room centers (\(^{room}\)) and 50 slicing boxes, which generally would be more than the ground-truth room centers \(}^{room}\) and slicing boxes \(\), respectively. Thus, following DETR , we conduct a set-based bipartite matching between predictions and targets in the center transformer \(_{center}\) and the box transformer \(_{box}\). Since we use the same strategy in both of the transformers, we explain this step using the center transformer \(_{center}\) as an example. Our goal is to optimize a bipartite matching objective on a permutation function \(():_{+}_{+}\) which maps \(\) prediction indices to \(M\) targets:

\[^{*}=_{}_{i=1}^{}_{\{(i) M \}}[_{1}d_{1}(c^{room}_{i},^{room}_{(i)})+_{ 2}d_{2}(p^{room}_{i})]\] (1)

where \(d_{1}(,)\) represents \(L_{1}\) distance between predicted and target room center coordinates, \(d_{2}()\) represents the focal loss between predicted and target room center probabilities, and \(_{\{\}}\) is an indicator function. Finally, we use the Hungarian Matching algorithm to calculate the minimal cost \(^{*}\) that maps \(\) predicted room centers to \(M\) target room centers and \(\) predicted slicing boxes to \(N\) target slicing boxes.

### Post-processing

Here, we describe the post-processing steps in Figure 5 to reconstruct the floorplan using the slicing boxes \(\) and room centers \(^{room}\) obtained in the previous step by the SLIBO-Net.

The first step in the post-processing phase is to cluster the slicing boxes \(\) into rooms. Given the predicted room centers \(^{room}\) from the center transformer \(_{center}\) and the predicted slicing boxes \(^{box}\) corresponded rooms' centers \(^{box}\) as the input, we can cluster the slicing boxes \(\) into different rooms by assigning the \(^{box}\) to the nearest room centers \(^{room}\) from the center transformer \(_{center}\).

After clustering the boxes into different rooms, we fill the gaps between the bottom and top of any two adjacent boxes in the same room with a box whose height is the vertical distance between them and whose width is the intersection length of them.

Finally, we union together the boxes for each room to form a room area \(A_{r}\). We then overlay \(A_{r}\) on the cell complex, which allows us to calculate the intersection ratio for each room per cell. By assigning each cell to the room with the largest intersection ratio, we can obtain a room representation by tracing the boundary formed by the cell groups. For non-connected components within a single room, we choose the component with the largest area. A cell remains empty if no room has more than 50% overlap.

